Investigating the TMDB Dataset¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This report will detail my exploration of the TMDB dataset. I found the dataset to be a rich dataset with many useful fields concerning traits of the movies (runtime, genre, etc...) as well as, of which of will be of particular focus in this report, their financial performance. Given the dataset includes budget and revenue figures, I thought it would be interesting to explore the idea of identifying financially-successful movies by their profit (budget subtracted from revenue) and return on investment (ROI; profit divided by budget), along with investigating associations with the other fields.

Data Wrangling¶

The wrangling of the dataset generally fell into the following three activities:

  1. The consideration of each field's relevance to potentially predicting a film's financial performance, and thus removing any columns deemed irrelevant to the study.
  2. The creation of additional fields, the profit and ROI fields and converting the genre text field into multiple binary variables.
  3. The removal of rows with missing and/or wrong data.
  4. Review of the distribution of dependent variables to prepare for multivariable analysis.

Given the presence of the adjusted budget and revenue figures, I think it would be straightforward to explore the correlation of the financial figures and the float fields, such as runtime (e.g do longer movies generate more revenue?) and vote average (e.g. how much do viewers' opinions of the movie correlate with financial return?). Additionally, the text fields, such as genre, may provide an opportunity for the generation of categorical variables.

Given that there is an adjusted budget field and adjusted revenue field, it should be simple to construct a profit and ROI field to assess the financial success of each movie.

From a quick wiki search, film budgeting might not include the promotional costs associated with the film (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Film_budgeting) nor goverment incentives, thus the crude "ROI" or "profit" used in this analysis is probably not the same value a financial analyst would use, but after creating the fields, I can check the top of the list to see if it appears to approximate the true financial/accounting values. For example, I would expect The Blair Witch Project, a famously low-budget and high-grossing movie, to rank towards the top ROI's in this list. Please note that, ideally, consultation with a domain expert would be helpful in advising if this is a worthwhile exploration.

Removing and Creating Columns¶

As the scope of the exploration has been defined, it now makes sense to review each of the fields and determine if they will be relevant to the exploration or if they may be dropped immediately.

Among the considerations include whether the variable may potentially determine the financial performance of the film, and whether the variable may be examined fruitfully given the scope of this project (i.e. may be examined without advanced modeling techniques) and the size of the dataset (e.g. avoiding the creation of thousands of variables for textual analysis).

I found all but one of the fields to be self-descriptive, and thus facilitated the decision on their inclusion or exclusion, with the exception being the popularity field.

The popularity field seemed to be a metric specific to the TMDB site, so I resorted to their support forums for more information.

From the Tmdb forums, there is a response concerning speculated changes to the metric:

"It's mostly the same as before. Unique views on the website but improved with taking in account the number of ratings a movie received, number of favourites and number of watched list additions all for the previous day. It also uses the part of the previous days score to help popularity trending and finally, boosts scores a tad if the newer a release date is."

Given that the metric includes the trendiness of a movie at a particular time, I would like to remove it and review what seem to be the inputs for the metric; release_date, vote_counts, and vote_average; separately, given that the metric seems to just to just be a combination of available fields with a recency bias.

Additionally, I will drop the following columns:

  • budget: using adjusted budget
  • revenue: using adjusted revenue
  • cast: too many values for categorical variables; risk overfitting
  • homepage: don't see any potential relevance
  • director: there could be thousands of directors in the set; too many values for categorical variables; risk overfitting
  • tagline: don't see any potential relevance
  • keywords: too many values for categorical variables; risk overfitting
  • overview: too many values for categorical variables; risk overfitting
  • production_companies: there could be thousands of production companies in the set; too many values for categorical variables; risk overfitting
  • release_date: could maybe be used to explore seasonality, but I think this would be a high-cost, low-reward exploration

There are now the following fields left:

  • original_title: This will help with spot-checking the data
  • runtime: I have a hunch that there's a "sweet spot" for movie runtimes
  • genres: unlike the directors, cast, and other text fields, I do think the set of genres is small enough to convert to a categorical variables with a binary field for each genre
  • vote_count: maybe captures the popularity of the movie; also, perhaps movies with very low vote counts can be disregarded in the analysis so the vote_averages won't be skewed
  • vote_average: how much viewers enjoyed the movie should definitely be explored as a predictor for the movie's success
  • release_year: the release year can perhaps allow the exploration of movie industry trend e.g. higher returns during a "boom" year for the movie industry as a whole
  • budget_adj: the adjusted figure will allow for a accurate comparison across years
  • revenue_adj: the adjusted figure will allow for a accurate comparison across years

I will now create the profit field, ROI field, and the genre binary variables.

In [6]:
df['profit'] = df.revenue_adj - df.budget_adj
df['ROI'] = df.profit/df.budget_adj

From reviewing the highest values, a lot of these runtimes look to be the result of total runtimes for series, like the series The Story of Film: An Odyssey and Band of Brother; also Taken looks to be the total runtime of the original and all of its sequels. Yet, there are entries with long runtimes that were intended to designated as feature length films, like Shoah). Therefore, I won't remove these entries for now, though I do see that many of these entries seem to be missing budget or revenue data, which will be removed anyways.

I am concerned by the zero minimums for the budgets and revenues. While I guess it is possible to produce a film without a budget or that doesn't generate revenue, I believe the bulk, if not all, of these cases will be missing data.

At this point, with familiar entries like Star Wars and Avatar for profit, along with Napoleon Dynamite and The Blair Witch Project for ROI, the metric does seem to be useful. Yet, while the top of the profit list seems legitimate, I'm unsure about the top of the ROI list.

Particularly, I'm skeptical of a few of the very small budgets producing the max ROI's. For example, I find it hard to believe that The Karate Kid, Part II had a budget of less than a thousand dollars.

From checking max values, the top 3, The Karate Kid, Part II, Into the Night), From Prada to Nada, look to have wrong budget numbers. The 4th and 5th highest, Paranormal Activity and the aforementioned Blair Witch Project, famously had low budgets, and I would expect them to be the max values.

I'm removing the top 3.

It appears that profits are right-skewed, though not nearly as right-skewed as the ROIs. With the profits, increasing the granularity of the histogram by increasing the number of bins reveals the "bell", while even with 100 bins for ROIs, there isn't a visible bell, indicating the distribution is heavily skewed to the right.

While simply removing the outliers might reveal a curve, I do think keeping the outliers would be worthwhile given that I confirmed that the max ROIs remaining in the dataset were legitimate values.

Also, given that an ROI cannot be less than -1, adding 1 to the ROIs and then taking the log of the values might yield a transformed distribution more amenable to multivariable analysis.

In [22]:
df['ROI_log'] = np.log(df['ROI'] + 1)
In [23]:
ax = df.ROI_log.hist(bins = 20);
ax.set_xlabel('log(ROI + 1)');
ax.set_ylabel('Frequency');
ax.set_title('ROI Log Transform Histogram');

It does appear that the log transform addressed the skew, and thus potentially addresses the max values from being over-weighted in the mutlivariable analysis. Therefore, I will keep the log transformation in the dataframe.

From reviewing the heatmap of the covariances, a lot of the significant covariances are intuitive. For example, adventure movies do seem to also be adventure movies, and animation movies also seem to tend to be family films.

I do think it would be interesting explore every permutation of genres to see if a particular combination seems to be profitable. I think in a more complex analysis (probably beyond the scope of this report) it might be worthwhile to fully explore the genres, given that the genre could potentially be a powerful predictor as the genre of the movie is decided early on in the movie production process, while something like review scores don't come until the movie is already produced.

Summary of Exploration¶

From the exploration of the fields, there are three main considerations:

  • The ROI metric in its original essentially failed to yield any signicant correlations
  • The log transform of the ROI and profit both yielded many correlations amongst the continuous variables
  • Only the profit metric yielded correlations with the genres

When reviewing the continuous variables, generating the scatter plots helped confirm the correlations calculated in the correlation table.

When reviewing the genres, using the adventure genre as a test, reviewing the distribution of adventure and non-adventure profits did seem support the significant covariance value shown in the heatmap.

Conclusions¶

Given there were a number of significant correlations found for both the continuous variables and the genres, I am most comfortable with saying that among the financial metrics, the profit metric is ready for a rudimentary model for multivariate regression analysis.

I believe that the profit field is most ready given that there were significant correlations for genres, and I think the genres have more predictive power than the other fields given that the genre for a movie is determined early on in the movie production process, and thus there is less concern with the nature of the causality in the relationship between profit and genre.

For the ROI metric, I think further mining of the dataset would be needed to generate more features for a predictive model. While the correlation with runtime perhaps revealed a significant feature, features like number of votes and vote scores might be more associative, and not as useful for predicting the financial performance of future movies. Also, the release year correlation (a slight inverse correlation) might simply be inherent to the dataset, with more recent movies having less time to generate profits.

Limitations and Further Considerations¶

While for the profit metric I think there may be enough features to draft a predictive model, I do think that for all the potential dependent variables, the dataset should be mined further with advanced techniques to generate more features.

For example, it might be worthwhile to further explore combinations of genres since that could increase the number of genre features. Additionally, perhaps with more advanced techniques, it would be worthwhile to explore the cast, director, and production movie fields, because, like genres, those traits are determined early in the movie production process. Also, exploring those text fields could potentially vastly increase the number of predictive features and could comprise a complex and powerful model.
